# Feature Files

This document describes the best practices and conventions for writing feature files in this project.

## Guidelines

- **Always check for reusable steps before writing feature files.** Reusable shared steps are defined in the `tests/e2e/step-definitions/shared` directory. Read them before writing any feature file and use them in the feature file scenarios if possible.
- **Create shared steps.** When creating a new step, ask yourself whether it is specific for the given feature or whether it could be made more generic. If it can be more generic, you can rewrite the step to be more generic and create a shared step in the shared steps directory. That way the step can be reused in other feature files.
- **Create feature scoped steps.** When creating a new step, it is possible that it will be specific to the given feature and won't be really reusable. In that case, create the steps in the `tests/e2e/step-definitions/` folder. Follow the same structure as in the `feature` folder.

### Naming conventions

Elements in code that are referred to in scenario steps should have a "data-test" attribute that will indicate the element.

Elements should be named and referred to in the format `"<element-name>-<element-type>"`. Examples:

- **Pages:** `"login-page"`, `"home-page"`, `"signup-page"`
- **Buttons:** `"login-button"`, `"submit-button"`
- **Input fields:** `"email-field"`, `"password-field"`
- **Links:** `"signup-link"`, `"login-link"`
- **Sections:** `"lesson-list-section"`
- **Headers:** `"course-name-header"`
- **Snackbar:** `"item-bought-snackbar"`

### Step Definitions

Cucumber steps should be defined in the `tests/e2e/step-definitions` directory. Step definitions should be organized in feature-based folders matching the `features/` directory structure (e.g. `features/auth/login.feature` → `tests/e2e/step-definitions/auth/login.steps.ts`).

#### Shared Steps

Shared steps are steps that are not feature scoped but are reusable across multiple feature files. You import and reuse shared steps whenever possible instead of duplicating logic.

Examples of shared steps:

- **Clicking**: `When I click the "login-button" button` uses shared click step
- **Input**: `When I enter "text@example.com" in the "email-field" field` uses shared input step
- **Navigation**: `Given I am on the "login-page" page` uses shared page visit step
- **Sections**: `Then I should see a "lesson-completed-section" section` uses shared section step

#### Feature-specific Steps

Only create feature-specific steps when shared steps cannot handle the scenario.

#### Naming

Step definition files should match feature file names (e.g., `login.steps.ts` for `login.feature`).
